songs.full_title: Strokin' by Clarence Carter
songs.title: Strokin’

description.plain: Strokin' was released in 1985, but only to jukeboxes as the record company said it was too raunchy to be a single or for public airplay. Bar patrons were the song’s biggest players, but this song found big acclaim when it was featured in Eddie Murphy’s raunchier remake of The Nutty Professor.

songs.full_title: Slip Away by Clarence Carter
songs.title: Slip Away

description.plain:
On the 1968 soul classic “Slip Away,” Clarence Carter asks a girl to cheat with him. “Slip Away” was originally a B-side to the single “Funky Fever,” which failed to do well on the charts.

Carter shared co-writing credits for “Slip Away” with friends William Armstrong and Wilbur Terrell—they didn’t contribute, but they were in bad financial shape and he wanted to help.
